=== CST ===
DOCUMENT@0..12600 {
  SUMMARY@0..101 {
    TEXT_LINE: "einsum(subscripts, *operands, out=None, dtype=None, order='K',"@0..62
    NEWLINE: "\n"@62..63
    WHITESPACE: "       "@63..70
    TEXT_LINE: "casting='safe', optimize=False)"@70..101
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@101..102
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@102..103
  EXTENDED_SUMMARY@103..639 {
    TEXT_LINE: "Evaluates the Einstein summation convention on the operands."@103..163
    NEWLINE: "\n"@163..164
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@164..165
    TEXT_LINE: "Using the Einstein summation convention, many common multi-dimensional,"@165..236
    NEWLINE: "\n"@236..237
    TEXT_LINE: "linear algebraic array operations can be represented in a simple fashion."@237..310
    NEWLINE: "\n"@310..311
    TEXT_LINE: "In *implicit* mode `einsum` computes these values."@311..361
    NEWLINE: "\n"@361..362
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@362..363
    TEXT_LINE: "In *explicit* mode, `einsum` provides further flexibility to compute"@363..431
    NEWLINE: "\n"@431..432
    TEXT_LINE: "other array operations that might not be considered classical Einstein"@432..502
    NEWLINE: "\n"@502..503
    TEXT_LINE: "summation operations, by disabling, or forcing summation over specified"@503..574
    NEWLINE: "\n"@574..575
    TEXT_LINE: "subscript labels."@575..592
    NEWLINE: "\n"@592..593
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@593..594
    TEXT_LINE: "See the notes and examples for clarification."@594..639
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@639..640
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@640..641
  SECTION@641..2650 {
    SECTION_HEADER@641..662 {
      NAME: "Parameters"@641..651
      NEWLINE: "\n"@651..652
      UNDERLINE: "----------"@652..662
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@662..663
    ENTRY@663..950 {
      NAME: "subscripts"@663..673
      WHITESPACE: " "@673..674
      COLON: ":"@674..675
      WHITESPACE: " "@675..676
      TYPE: "str"@676..679
      NEWLINE: "\n"@679..680
      WHITESPACE: "    "@680..684
      DESCRIPTION@684..950 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Specifies the subscripts for summation as comma separated list of"@684..749
        NEWLINE: "\n"@749..750
        WHITESPACE: "    "@750..754
        TEXT_LINE: "subscript labels. An implicit (classical Einstein summation)"@754..814
        NEWLINE: "\n"@814..815
        WHITESPACE: "    "@815..819
        TEXT_LINE: "calculation is performed unless the explicit indicator '->' is"@819..881
        NEWLINE: "\n"@881..882
        WHITESPACE: "    "@882..886
        TEXT_LINE: "included as well as subscript labels of the precise output form."@886..950
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@950..951
    ENTRY@951..1024 {
      NAME: "operands"@951..959
      WHITESPACE: " "@959..960
      COLON: ":"@960..961
      WHITESPACE: " "@961..962
      TYPE: "list of array_like"@962..980
      NEWLINE: "\n"@980..981
      WHITESPACE: "    "@981..985
      DESCRIPTION@985..1024 {
        TEXT_LINE: "These are the arrays for the operation."@985..1024
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1024..1025
    ENTRY@1025..1106 {
      NAME: "out"@1025..1028
      WHITESPACE: " "@1028..1029
      COLON: ":"@1029..1030
      WHITESPACE: " "@1030..1031
      TYPE: "ndarray"@1031..1038
      COMMA: ","@1038..1039
      WHITESPACE: " "@1039..1040
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@1040..1048
      NEWLINE: "\n"@1048..1049
      WHITESPACE: "    "@1049..1053
      DESCRIPTION@1053..1106 {
        TEXT_LINE: "If provided, the calculation is done into this array."@1053..1106
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1106..1107
    ENTRY@1107..1336 {
      NAME: "dtype"@1107..1112
      WHITESPACE: " "@1112..1113
      COLON: ":"@1113..1114
      WHITESPACE: " "@1114..1115
      TYPE: "{data-type, None}"@1115..1132
      COMMA: ","@1132..1133
      WHITESPACE: " "@1133..1134
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@1134..1142
      NEWLINE: "\n"@1142..1143
      WHITESPACE: "    "@1143..1147
      DESCRIPTION@1147..1336 {
        TEXT_LINE: "If provided, forces the calculation to use the data type specified."@1147..1214
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1214..1215
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1215..1219
        TEXT_LINE: "Note that you may have to also give a more liberal `casting`"@1219..1279
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1279..1280
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1280..1284
        TEXT_LINE: "parameter to allow the conversions. Default is None."@1284..1336
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1336..1337
    ENTRY@1337..1719 {
      NAME: "order"@1337..1342
      WHITESPACE: " "@1342..1343
      COLON: ":"@1343..1344
      WHITESPACE: " "@1344..1345
      TYPE: "{'C', 'F', 'A', 'K'}"@1345..1365
      COMMA: ","@1365..1366
      WHITESPACE: " "@1366..1367
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@1367..1375
      NEWLINE: "\n"@1375..1376
      WHITESPACE: "    "@1376..1380
      DESCRIPTION@1380..1719 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Controls the memory layout of the output. 'C' means it should"@1380..1441
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1441..1442
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1442..1446
        TEXT_LINE: "be C contiguous. 'F' means it should be Fortran contiguous,"@1446..1505
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1505..1506
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1506..1510
        TEXT_LINE: "'A' means it should be 'F' if the inputs are all 'F', 'C' otherwise."@1510..1578
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1578..1579
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1579..1583
        TEXT_LINE: "'K' means it should be as close to the layout as the inputs as"@1583..1645
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1645..1646
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1646..1650
        TEXT_LINE: "is possible, including arbitrarily permuted axes."@1650..1699
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1699..1700
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1700..1704
        TEXT_LINE: "Default is 'K'."@1704..1719
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1719..1720
    ENTRY@1720..2301 {
      NAME: "casting"@1720..1727
      WHITESPACE: " "@1727..1728
      COLON: ":"@1728..1729
      WHITESPACE: " "@1729..1730
      TYPE: "{'no', 'equiv', 'safe', 'same_kind', 'unsafe'}"@1730..1776
      COMMA: ","@1776..1777
      WHITESPACE: " "@1777..1778
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@1778..1786
      NEWLINE: "\n"@1786..1787
      WHITESPACE: "    "@1787..1791
      DESCRIPTION@1791..2301 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Controls what kind of data casting may occur.  Setting this to"@1791..1853
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1853..1854
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1854..1858
        TEXT_LINE: "'unsafe' is not recommended, as it can adversely affect accumulations."@1858..1928
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1928..1929
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1929..1930
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1930..1934
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'no' means the data types should not be cast at all."@1934..1988
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1988..1989
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1989..1993
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'equiv' means only byte-order changes are allowed."@1993..2045
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2045..2046
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2046..2050
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'safe' means only casts which can preserve values are allowed."@2050..2114
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2114..2115
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2115..2119
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'same_kind' means only safe casts or casts within a kind,"@2119..2178
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2178..2179
        WHITESPACE: "      "@2179..2185
        TEXT_LINE: "like float64 to float32, are allowed."@2185..2222
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2222..2223
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2223..2227
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'unsafe' means any data conversions may be done."@2227..2277
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2277..2278
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2278..2279
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2279..2283
        TEXT_LINE: "Default is 'safe'."@2283..2301
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2301..2302
    ENTRY@2302..2650 {
      NAME: "optimize"@2302..2310
      WHITESPACE: " "@2310..2311
      COLON: ":"@2311..2312
      WHITESPACE: " "@2312..2313
      TYPE: "{False, True, 'greedy', 'optimal'}"@2313..2347
      COMMA: ","@2347..2348
      WHITESPACE: " "@2348..2349
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@2349..2357
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2357..2358
      WHITESPACE: "    "@2358..2362
      DESCRIPTION@2362..2650 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Controls if intermediate optimization should occur. No optimization"@2362..2429
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2429..2430
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2430..2434
        TEXT_LINE: "will occur if False and True will default to the 'greedy' algorithm."@2434..2502
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2502..2503
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2503..2507
        TEXT_LINE: "Also accepts an explicit contraction list from the ``np.einsum_path``"@2507..2576
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2576..2577
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2577..2581
        TEXT_LINE: "function. See ``np.einsum_path`` for more details. Defaults to False."@2581..2650
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@2650..2651
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2651..2652
  SECTION@2652..2748 {
    SECTION_HEADER@2652..2667 {
      NAME: "Returns"@2652..2659
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2659..2660
      UNDERLINE: "-------"@2660..2667
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2667..2668
    ENTRY@2668..2748 {
      NAME: "output"@2668..2674
      WHITESPACE: " "@2674..2675
      COLON: ":"@2675..2676
      WHITESPACE: " "@2676..2677
      TYPE: "ndarray"@2677..2684
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2684..2685
      WHITESPACE: "    "@2685..2689
      DESCRIPTION@2689..2748 {
        TEXT_LINE: "The calculation based on the Einstein summation convention."@2689..2748
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@2748..2749
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2749..2750
  SECTION@2750..3229 {
    SECTION_HEADER@2750..2767 {
      NAME: "See Also"@2750..2758
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2758..2759
      UNDERLINE: "--------"@2759..2767
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2767..2768
    ENTRY@2768..2827 {
      NAME: "einsum_path"@2768..2779
      COMMA: ","@2779..2780
      WHITESPACE: " "@2780..2781
      NAME: "dot"@2781..2784
      COMMA: ","@2784..2785
      WHITESPACE: " "@2785..2786
      NAME: "inner"@2786..2791
      COMMA: ","@2791..2792
      WHITESPACE: " "@2792..2793
      NAME: "outer"@2793..2798
      COMMA: ","@2798..2799
      WHITESPACE: " "@2799..2800
      NAME: "tensordot"@2800..2809
      COMMA: ","@2809..2810
      WHITESPACE: " "@2810..2811
      NAME: "linalg.multi_dot"@2811..2827
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2827..2828
    ENTRY@2828..3229 {
      NAME: "einsum"@2828..2834
      COLON: ":"@2834..2835
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2835..2836
      WHITESPACE: "    "@2836..2840
      DESCRIPTION@2840..3229 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Similar verbose interface is provided by the"@2840..2884
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2884..2885
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2885..2889
        TEXT_LINE: "`einops <https://github.com/arogozhnikov/einops>`_ package to cover"@2889..2956
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2956..2957
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2957..2961
        TEXT_LINE: "additional operations: transpose, reshape/flatten, repeat/tile,"@2961..3024
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3024..3025
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3025..3029
        TEXT_LINE: "squeeze/unsqueeze and reductions."@3029..3062
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3062..3063
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3063..3067
        TEXT_LINE: "The `opt_einsum <https://optimized-einsum.readthedocs.io/en/stable/>`_"@3067..3137
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3137..3138
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3138..3142
        TEXT_LINE: "optimizes contraction order for einsum-like expressions"@3142..3197
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3197..3198
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3198..3202
        TEXT_LINE: "in backend-agnostic manner."@3202..3229
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@3229..3230
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@3230..3231
  SECTION@3231..8166 {
    SECTION_HEADER@3231..3242 {
      NAME: "Notes"@3231..3236
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3236..3237
      UNDERLINE: "-----"@3237..3242
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@3242..3243
    DESCRIPTION@3243..8166 {
      TEXT_LINE: "The Einstein summation convention can be used to compute"@3243..3299
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3299..3300
      TEXT_LINE: "many multi-dimensional, linear algebraic array operations. `einsum`"@3300..3367
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3367..3368
      TEXT_LINE: "provides a succinct way of representing these."@3368..3414
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3414..3415
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@3415..3416
      TEXT_LINE: "A non-exhaustive list of these operations,"@3416..3458
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3458..3459
      TEXT_LINE: "which can be computed by `einsum`, is shown below along with examples:"@3459..3529
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3529..3530
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@3530..3531
      TEXT_LINE: "* Trace of an array, :py:func:`numpy.trace`."@3531..3575
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3575..3576
      TEXT_LINE: "* Return a diagonal, :py:func:`numpy.diag`."@3576..3619
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3619..3620
      TEXT_LINE: "* Array axis summations, :py:func:`numpy.sum`."@3620..3666
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3666..3667
      TEXT_LINE: "* Transpositions and permutations, :py:func:`numpy.transpose`."@3667..3729
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3729..3730
      TEXT_LINE: "* Matrix multiplication and dot product, :py:func:`numpy.matmul`"@3730..3794
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3794..3795
      WHITESPACE: "    "@3795..3799
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`numpy.dot`."@3799..3820
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3820..3821
      TEXT_LINE: "* Vector inner and outer products, :py:func:`numpy.inner`"@3821..3878
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3878..3879
      WHITESPACE: "    "@3879..3883
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`numpy.outer`."@3883..3906
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3906..3907
      TEXT_LINE: "* Broadcasting, element-wise and scalar multiplication,"@3907..3962
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3962..3963
      WHITESPACE: "    "@3963..3967
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`numpy.multiply`."@3967..3993
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3993..3994
      TEXT_LINE: "* Tensor contractions, :py:func:`numpy.tensordot`."@3994..4044
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4044..4045
      TEXT_LINE: "* Chained array operations, in efficient calculation order,"@4045..4104
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4104..4105
      WHITESPACE: "    "@4105..4109
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`numpy.einsum_path`."@4109..4138
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4138..4139
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4139..4140
      TEXT_LINE: "The subscripts string is a comma-separated list of subscript labels,"@4140..4208
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4208..4209
      TEXT_LINE: "where each label refers to a dimension of the corresponding operand."@4209..4277
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4277..4278
      TEXT_LINE: "Whenever a label is repeated it is summed, so ``np.einsum('i,i', a, b)``"@4278..4350
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4350..4351
      TEXT_LINE: "is equivalent to :py:func:`np.inner(a,b) <numpy.inner>`. If a label"@4351..4418
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4418..4419
      TEXT_LINE: "appears only once, it is not summed, so ``np.einsum('i', a)``"@4419..4480
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4480..4481
      TEXT_LINE: "produces a view of ``a`` with no changes. A further example"@4481..4540
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4540..4541
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('ij,jk', a, b)`` describes traditional matrix multiplication"@4541..4613
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4613..4614
      TEXT_LINE: "and is equivalent to :py:func:`np.matmul(a,b) <numpy.matmul>`."@4614..4676
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4676..4677
      TEXT_LINE: "Repeated subscript labels in one operand take the diagonal."@4677..4736
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4736..4737
      TEXT_LINE: "For example, ``np.einsum('ii', a)`` is equivalent to"@4737..4789
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4789..4790
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`np.trace(a) <numpy.trace>`."@4790..4827
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4827..4828
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4828..4829
      TEXT_LINE: "In *implicit mode*, the chosen subscripts are important"@4829..4884
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4884..4885
      TEXT_LINE: "since the axes of the output are reordered alphabetically.  This"@4885..4949
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4949..4950
      TEXT_LINE: "means that ``np.einsum('ij', a)`` doesn't affect a 2D array, while"@4950..5016
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5016..5017
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('ji', a)`` takes its transpose. Additionally,"@5017..5074
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5074..5075
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('ij,jk', a, b)`` returns a matrix multiplication, while,"@5075..5143
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5143..5144
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('ij,jh', a, b)`` returns the transpose of the"@5144..5201
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5201..5202
      TEXT_LINE: "multiplication since subscript 'h' precedes subscript 'i'."@5202..5260
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5260..5261
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@5261..5262
      TEXT_LINE: "In *explicit mode* the output can be directly controlled by"@5262..5321
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5321..5322
      TEXT_LINE: "specifying output subscript labels.  This requires the"@5322..5376
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5376..5377
      TEXT_LINE: "identifier '->' as well as the list of output subscript labels."@5377..5440
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5440..5441
      TEXT_LINE: "This feature increases the flexibility of the function since"@5441..5501
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5501..5502
      TEXT_LINE: "summing can be disabled or forced when required. The call"@5502..5559
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5559..5560
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('i->', a)`` is like :py:func:`np.sum(a) <numpy.sum>`"@5560..5624
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5624..5625
      TEXT_LINE: "if ``a`` is a 1-D array, and ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)``"@5625..5679
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5679..5680
      TEXT_LINE: "is like :py:func:`np.diag(a) <numpy.diag>` if ``a`` is a square 2-D array."@5680..5754
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5754..5755
      TEXT_LINE: "The difference is that `einsum` does not allow broadcasting by default."@5755..5826
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5826..5827
      TEXT_LINE: "Additionally ``np.einsum('ij,jh->ih', a, b)`` directly specifies the"@5827..5895
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5895..5896
      TEXT_LINE: "order of the output subscript labels and therefore returns matrix"@5896..5961
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5961..5962
      TEXT_LINE: "multiplication, unlike the example above in implicit mode."@5962..6020
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6020..6021
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@6021..6022
      TEXT_LINE: "To enable and control broadcasting, use an ellipsis.  Default"@6022..6083
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6083..6084
      TEXT_LINE: "NumPy-style broadcasting is done by adding an ellipsis"@6084..6138
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6138..6139
      TEXT_LINE: "to the left of each term, like ``np.einsum('...ii->...i', a)``."@6139..6202
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6202..6203
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('...i->...', a)`` is like"@6203..6240
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6240..6241
      TEXT_LINE: ":py:func:`np.sum(a, axis=-1) <numpy.sum>` for array ``a`` of any shape."@6241..6312
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6312..6313
      TEXT_LINE: "To take the trace along the first and last axes,"@6313..6361
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6361..6362
      TEXT_LINE: "you can do ``np.einsum('i...i', a)``, or to do a matrix-matrix"@6362..6424
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6424..6425
      TEXT_LINE: "product with the left-most indices instead of rightmost, one can do"@6425..6492
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6492..6493
      TEXT_LINE: "``np.einsum('ij...,jk...->ik...', a, b)``."@6493..6535
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6535..6536
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@6536..6537
      TEXT_LINE: "When there is only one operand, no axes are summed, and no output"@6537..6602
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6602..6603
      TEXT_LINE: "parameter is provided, a view into the operand is returned instead"@6603..6669
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6669..6670
      TEXT_LINE: "of a new array.  Thus, taking the diagonal as ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)``"@6670..6741
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6741..6742
      TEXT_LINE: "produces a view (changed in version 1.10.0)."@6742..6786
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6786..6787
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@6787..6788
      TEXT_LINE: "`einsum` also provides an alternative way to provide the subscripts and"@6788..6859
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6859..6860
      TEXT_LINE: "operands as ``einsum(op0, sublist0, op1, sublist1, ..., [sublistout])``."@6860..6932
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6932..6933
      TEXT_LINE: "If the output shape is not provided in this format `einsum` will be"@6933..7000
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7000..7001
      TEXT_LINE: "calculated in implicit mode, otherwise it will be performed explicitly."@7001..7072
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7072..7073
      TEXT_LINE: "The examples below have corresponding `einsum` calls with the two"@7073..7138
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7138..7139
      TEXT_LINE: "parameter methods."@7139..7157
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7157..7158
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7158..7159
      TEXT_LINE: "Views returned from einsum are now writeable whenever the input array"@7159..7228
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7228..7229
      TEXT_LINE: "is writeable. For example, ``np.einsum('ijk...->kji...', a)`` will now"@7229..7299
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7299..7300
      TEXT_LINE: "have the same effect as :py:func:`np.swapaxes(a, 0, 2) <numpy.swapaxes>`"@7300..7372
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7372..7373
      TEXT_LINE: "and ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)`` will return a writeable view of the diagonal"@7373..7447
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7447..7448
      TEXT_LINE: "of a 2D array."@7448..7462
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7462..7463
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7463..7464
      TEXT_LINE: "Added the ``optimize`` argument which will optimize the contraction order"@7464..7537
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7537..7538
      TEXT_LINE: "of an einsum expression. For a contraction with three or more operands"@7538..7608
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7608..7609
      TEXT_LINE: "this can greatly increase the computational efficiency at the cost of"@7609..7678
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7678..7679
      TEXT_LINE: "a larger memory footprint during computation."@7679..7724
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7724..7725
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7725..7726
      TEXT_LINE: "Typically a 'greedy' algorithm is applied which empirical tests have shown"@7726..7800
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7800..7801
      TEXT_LINE: "returns the optimal path in the majority of cases. In some cases 'optimal'"@7801..7875
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7875..7876
      TEXT_LINE: "will return the superlative path through a more expensive, exhaustive"@7876..7945
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7945..7946
      TEXT_LINE: "search. For iterative calculations it may be advisable to calculate"@7946..8013
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8013..8014
      TEXT_LINE: "the optimal path once and reuse that path by supplying it as an argument."@8014..8087
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8087..8088
      TEXT_LINE: "An example is given below."@8088..8114
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8114..8115
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8115..8116
      TEXT_LINE: "See :py:func:`numpy.einsum_path` for more details."@8116..8166
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@8166..8167
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8167..8168
  SECTION@8168..12600 {
    SECTION_HEADER@8168..8185 {
      NAME: "Examples"@8168..8176
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8176..8177
      UNDERLINE: "--------"@8177..8185
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@8185..8186
    DESCRIPTION@8186..12600 {
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a = np.arange(25).reshape(5,5)"@8186..8220
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8220..8221
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> b = np.arange(5)"@8221..8241
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8241..8242
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> c = np.arange(6).reshape(2,3)"@8242..8275
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8275..8276
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8276..8277
      TEXT_LINE: "Trace of a matrix:"@8277..8295
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8295..8296
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8296..8297
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ii', a)"@8297..8319
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8319..8320
      TEXT_LINE: "60"@8320..8322
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8322..8323
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [0,0])"@8323..8346
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8346..8347
      TEXT_LINE: "60"@8347..8349
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8349..8350
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.trace(a)"@8350..8365
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8365..8366
      TEXT_LINE: "60"@8366..8368
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8368..8369
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8369..8370
      TEXT_LINE: "Extract the diagonal (requires explicit form):"@8370..8416
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8416..8417
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8417..8418
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ii->i', a)"@8418..8443
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8443..8444
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])"@8444..8471
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8471..8472
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [0,0], [0])"@8472..8500
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8500..8501
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])"@8501..8528
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8528..8529
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.diag(a)"@8529..8543
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8543..8544
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])"@8544..8571
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8571..8572
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8572..8573
      TEXT_LINE: "Sum over an axis (requires explicit form):"@8573..8615
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8615..8616
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8616..8617
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ij->i', a)"@8617..8642
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8642..8643
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])"@8643..8675
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8675..8676
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [0,1], [0])"@8676..8704
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8704..8705
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])"@8705..8737
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8737..8738
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.sum(a, axis=1)"@8738..8759
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8759..8760
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])"@8760..8792
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8792..8793
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8793..8794
      TEXT_LINE: "For higher dimensional arrays summing a single axis can be done"@8794..8857
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8857..8858
      TEXT_LINE: "with ellipsis:"@8858..8872
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8872..8873
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8873..8874
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('...j->...', a)"@8874..8903
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8903..8904
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])"@8904..8936
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8936..8937
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [Ellipsis,1], [Ellipsis])"@8937..8979
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8979..8980
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])"@8980..9012
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9012..9013
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9013..9014
      TEXT_LINE: "Compute a matrix transpose, or reorder any number of axes:"@9014..9072
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9072..9073
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9073..9074
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ji', c)"@9074..9096
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9096..9097
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 3],"@9097..9111
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9111..9112
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9112..9119
      TEXT_LINE: "[1, 4],"@9119..9126
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9126..9127
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9127..9134
      TEXT_LINE: "[2, 5]])"@9134..9142
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9142..9143
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ij->ji', c)"@9143..9169
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9169..9170
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 3],"@9170..9184
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9184..9185
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9185..9192
      TEXT_LINE: "[1, 4],"@9192..9199
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9199..9200
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9200..9207
      TEXT_LINE: "[2, 5]])"@9207..9215
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9215..9216
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(c, [1,0])"@9216..9239
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9239..9240
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 3],"@9240..9254
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9254..9255
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9255..9262
      TEXT_LINE: "[1, 4],"@9262..9269
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9269..9270
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9270..9277
      TEXT_LINE: "[2, 5]])"@9277..9285
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9285..9286
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.transpose(c)"@9286..9305
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9305..9306
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 3],"@9306..9320
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9320..9321
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9321..9328
      TEXT_LINE: "[1, 4],"@9328..9335
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9335..9336
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9336..9343
      TEXT_LINE: "[2, 5]])"@9343..9351
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9351..9352
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9352..9353
      TEXT_LINE: "Vector inner products:"@9353..9375
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9375..9376
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9376..9377
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('i,i', b, b)"@9377..9403
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9403..9404
      TEXT_LINE: "30"@9404..9406
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9406..9407
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(b, [0], b, [0])"@9407..9436
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9436..9437
      TEXT_LINE: "30"@9437..9439
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9439..9440
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.inner(b,b)"@9440..9457
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9457..9458
      TEXT_LINE: "30"@9458..9460
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9460..9461
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9461..9462
      TEXT_LINE: "Matrix vector multiplication:"@9462..9491
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9491..9492
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9492..9493
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ij,j', a, b)"@9493..9520
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9520..9521
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])"@9521..9553
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9553..9554
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [0,1], b, [1])"@9554..9585
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9585..9586
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])"@9586..9618
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9618..9619
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.dot(a, b)"@9619..9635
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9635..9636
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])"@9636..9668
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9668..9669
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('...j,j', a, b)"@9669..9698
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9698..9699
      TEXT_LINE: "array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])"@9699..9731
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9731..9732
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9732..9733
      TEXT_LINE: "Broadcasting and scalar multiplication:"@9733..9772
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9772..9773
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9773..9774
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('..., ...', 3, c)"@9774..9805
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9805..9806
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[ 0,  3,  6],"@9806..9826
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9826..9827
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9827..9834
      TEXT_LINE: "[ 9, 12, 15]])"@9834..9848
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9848..9849
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(',ij', 3, c)"@9849..9875
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9875..9876
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[ 0,  3,  6],"@9876..9896
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9896..9897
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9897..9904
      TEXT_LINE: "[ 9, 12, 15]])"@9904..9918
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9918..9919
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(3, [Ellipsis], c, [Ellipsis])"@9919..9962
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9962..9963
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[ 0,  3,  6],"@9963..9983
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9983..9984
      WHITESPACE: "       "@9984..9991
      TEXT_LINE: "[ 9, 12, 15]])"@9991..10005
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10005..10006
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.multiply(3, c)"@10006..10027
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10027..10028
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[ 0,  3,  6],"@10028..10048
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10048..10049
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10049..10056
      TEXT_LINE: "[ 9, 12, 15]])"@10056..10070
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10070..10071
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10071..10072
      TEXT_LINE: "Vector outer product:"@10072..10093
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10093..10094
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10094..10095
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('i,j', np.arange(2)+1, b)"@10095..10134
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10134..10135
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],"@10135..10158
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10158..10159
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10159..10166
      TEXT_LINE: "[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])"@10166..10183
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10183..10184
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(np.arange(2)+1, [0], b, [1])"@10184..10226
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10226..10227
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],"@10227..10250
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10250..10251
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10251..10258
      TEXT_LINE: "[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])"@10258..10275
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10275..10276
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.outer(np.arange(2)+1, b)"@10276..10307
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10307..10308
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],"@10308..10331
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10331..10332
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10332..10339
      TEXT_LINE: "[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])"@10339..10356
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10356..10357
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10357..10358
      TEXT_LINE: "Tensor contraction:"@10358..10377
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10377..10378
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10378..10379
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a = np.arange(60.).reshape(3,4,5)"@10379..10416
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10416..10417
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> b = np.arange(24.).reshape(4,3,2)"@10417..10454
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10454..10455
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ijk,jil->kl', a, b)"@10455..10489
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10489..10490
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[4400., 4730.],"@10490..10512
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10512..10513
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10513..10520
      TEXT_LINE: "[4532., 4874.],"@10520..10535
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10535..10536
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10536..10543
      TEXT_LINE: "[4664., 5018.],"@10543..10558
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10558..10559
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10559..10566
      TEXT_LINE: "[4796., 5162.],"@10566..10581
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10581..10582
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10582..10589
      TEXT_LINE: "[4928., 5306.]])"@10589..10605
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10605..10606
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum(a, [0,1,2], b, [1,0,3], [2,3])"@10606..10650
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10650..10651
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[4400., 4730.],"@10651..10673
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10673..10674
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10674..10681
      TEXT_LINE: "[4532., 4874.],"@10681..10696
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10696..10697
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10697..10704
      TEXT_LINE: "[4664., 5018.],"@10704..10719
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10719..10720
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10720..10727
      TEXT_LINE: "[4796., 5162.],"@10727..10742
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10742..10743
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10743..10750
      TEXT_LINE: "[4928., 5306.]])"@10750..10766
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10766..10767
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.tensordot(a,b, axes=([1,0],[0,1]))"@10767..10808
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10808..10809
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[4400., 4730.],"@10809..10831
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10831..10832
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10832..10839
      TEXT_LINE: "[4532., 4874.],"@10839..10854
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10854..10855
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10855..10862
      TEXT_LINE: "[4664., 5018.],"@10862..10877
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10877..10878
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10878..10885
      TEXT_LINE: "[4796., 5162.],"@10885..10900
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10900..10901
      WHITESPACE: "       "@10901..10908
      TEXT_LINE: "[4928., 5306.]])"@10908..10924
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10924..10925
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10925..10926
      TEXT_LINE: "Writeable returned arrays (since version 1.10.0):"@10926..10975
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10975..10976
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10976..10977
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a = np.zeros((3, 3))"@10977..11001
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11001..11002
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ii->i', a)[:] = 1"@11002..11034
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11034..11035
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a"@11035..11040
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11040..11041
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[1., 0., 0.],"@11041..11061
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11061..11062
      WHITESPACE: "       "@11062..11069
      TEXT_LINE: "[0., 1., 0.],"@11069..11082
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11082..11083
      WHITESPACE: "       "@11083..11090
      TEXT_LINE: "[0., 0., 1.]])"@11090..11104
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11104..11105
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11105..11106
      TEXT_LINE: "Example of ellipsis use:"@11106..11130
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11130..11131
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11131..11132
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a = np.arange(6).reshape((3,2))"@11132..11167
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11167..11168
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> b = np.arange(12).reshape((4,3))"@11168..11204
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11204..11205
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ki,jk->ij', a, b)"@11205..11237
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11237..11238
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[10, 28, 46, 64],"@11238..11262
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11262..11263
      WHITESPACE: "       "@11263..11270
      TEXT_LINE: "[13, 40, 67, 94]])"@11270..11288
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11288..11289
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('ki,...k->i...', a, b)"@11289..11325
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11325..11326
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[10, 28, 46, 64],"@11326..11350
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11350..11351
      WHITESPACE: "       "@11351..11358
      TEXT_LINE: "[13, 40, 67, 94]])"@11358..11376
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11376..11377
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.einsum('k...,jk', a, b)"@11377..11407
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11407..11408
      TEXT_LINE: "array([[10, 28, 46, 64],"@11408..11432
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11432..11433
      WHITESPACE: "       "@11433..11440
      TEXT_LINE: "[13, 40, 67, 94]])"@11440..11458
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11458..11459
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11459..11460
      TEXT_LINE: "Chained array operations. For more complicated contractions, speed ups"@11460..11530
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11530..11531
      TEXT_LINE: "might be achieved by repeatedly computing a 'greedy' path or pre-computing"@11531..11605
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11605..11606
      TEXT_LINE: "the 'optimal' path and repeatedly applying it, using an `einsum_path`"@11606..11675
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11675..11676
      TEXT_LINE: "insertion (since version 1.12.0). Performance improvements can be"@11676..11741
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11741..11742
      TEXT_LINE: "particularly significant with larger arrays:"@11742..11786
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11786..11787
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11787..11788
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> a = np.ones(64).reshape(2,4,8)"@11788..11822
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11822..11823
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11823..11824
      TEXT_LINE: "Basic `einsum`: ~1520ms  (benchmarked on 3.1GHz Intel i5.)"@11824..11882
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11882..11883
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11883..11884
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> for iteration in range(500):"@11884..11916
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11916..11917
      TEXT_LINE: "...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a)"@11917..11973
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11973..11974
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11974..11975
      TEXT_LINE: "Sub-optimal `einsum` (due to repeated path calculation time): ~330ms"@11975..12043
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12043..12044
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12044..12045
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> for iteration in range(500):"@12045..12077
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12077..12078
      TEXT_LINE: "...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a,"@12078..12134
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12134..12135
      TEXT_LINE: "...         optimize='optimal')"@12135..12166
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12166..12167
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12167..12168
      TEXT_LINE: "Greedy `einsum` (faster optimal path approximation): ~160ms"@12168..12227
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12227..12228
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12228..12229
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> for iteration in range(500):"@12229..12261
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12261..12262
      TEXT_LINE: "...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a, optimize='greedy')"@12262..12337
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12337..12338
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12338..12339
      TEXT_LINE: "Optimal `einsum` (best usage pattern in some use cases): ~110ms"@12339..12402
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12402..12403
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12403..12404
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> path = np.einsum_path('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a,"@12404..12464
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12464..12465
      TEXT_LINE: "...     optimize='optimal')[0]"@12465..12495
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12495..12496
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> for iteration in range(500):"@12496..12528
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12528..12529
      TEXT_LINE: "...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a, optimize=path)"@12529..12600
    }
  }
}
=== EMIT ===
einsum(subscripts, *operands, out=None, dtype=None, order='K',
       casting='safe', optimize=False)

Evaluates the Einstein summation convention on the operands.

Using the Einstein summation convention, many common multi-dimensional,
linear algebraic array operations can be represented in a simple fashion.
In *implicit* mode `einsum` computes these values.

In *explicit* mode, `einsum` provides further flexibility to compute
other array operations that might not be considered classical Einstein
summation operations, by disabling, or forcing summation over specified
subscript labels.

See the notes and examples for clarification.

Parameters
----------
subscripts : str
    Specifies the subscripts for summation as comma separated list of
    subscript labels. An implicit (classical Einstein summation)
    calculation is performed unless the explicit indicator '->' is
    included as well as subscript labels of the precise output form.
operands : list of array_like
    These are the arrays for the operation.
out : ndarray, optional
    If provided, the calculation is done into this array.
dtype : {data-type, None}, optional
    If provided, forces the calculation to use the data type specified.
    Note that you may have to also give a more liberal `casting`
    parameter to allow the conversions. Default is None.
order : {'C', 'F', 'A', 'K'}, optional
    Controls the memory layout of the output. 'C' means it should
    be C contiguous. 'F' means it should be Fortran contiguous,
    'A' means it should be 'F' if the inputs are all 'F', 'C' otherwise.
    'K' means it should be as close to the layout as the inputs as
    is possible, including arbitrarily permuted axes.
    Default is 'K'.
casting : {'no', 'equiv', 'safe', 'same_kind', 'unsafe'}, optional
    Controls what kind of data casting may occur.  Setting this to
    'unsafe' is not recommended, as it can adversely affect accumulations.

    * 'no' means the data types should not be cast at all.
    * 'equiv' means only byte-order changes are allowed.
    * 'safe' means only casts which can preserve values are allowed.
    * 'same_kind' means only safe casts or casts within a kind,
      like float64 to float32, are allowed.
    * 'unsafe' means any data conversions may be done.

    Default is 'safe'.
optimize : {False, True, 'greedy', 'optimal'}, optional
    Controls if intermediate optimization should occur. No optimization
    will occur if False and True will default to the 'greedy' algorithm.
    Also accepts an explicit contraction list from the ``np.einsum_path``
    function. See ``np.einsum_path`` for more details. Defaults to False.

Returns
-------
output : ndarray
    The calculation based on the Einstein summation convention.

See Also
--------
einsum_path, dot, inner, outer, tensordot, linalg.multi_dot
einsum : Similar verbose interface is provided by the
`einops <https://github.com/arogozhnikov/einops>`_ package to cover
additional operations: transpose, reshape/flatten, repeat/tile,
squeeze/unsqueeze and reductions.
The `opt_einsum <https://optimized-einsum.readthedocs.io/en/stable/>`_
optimizes contraction order for einsum-like expressions
in backend-agnostic manner.

Notes
-----
The Einstein summation convention can be used to compute
many multi-dimensional, linear algebraic array operations. `einsum`
provides a succinct way of representing these.

A non-exhaustive list of these operations,
which can be computed by `einsum`, is shown below along with examples:

* Trace of an array, :py:func:`numpy.trace`.
* Return a diagonal, :py:func:`numpy.diag`.
* Array axis summations, :py:func:`numpy.sum`.
* Transpositions and permutations, :py:func:`numpy.transpose`.
* Matrix multiplication and dot product, :py:func:`numpy.matmul`
    :py:func:`numpy.dot`.
* Vector inner and outer products, :py:func:`numpy.inner`
    :py:func:`numpy.outer`.
* Broadcasting, element-wise and scalar multiplication,
    :py:func:`numpy.multiply`.
* Tensor contractions, :py:func:`numpy.tensordot`.
* Chained array operations, in efficient calculation order,
    :py:func:`numpy.einsum_path`.

The subscripts string is a comma-separated list of subscript labels,
where each label refers to a dimension of the corresponding operand.
Whenever a label is repeated it is summed, so ``np.einsum('i,i', a, b)``
is equivalent to :py:func:`np.inner(a,b) <numpy.inner>`. If a label
appears only once, it is not summed, so ``np.einsum('i', a)``
produces a view of ``a`` with no changes. A further example
``np.einsum('ij,jk', a, b)`` describes traditional matrix multiplication
and is equivalent to :py:func:`np.matmul(a,b) <numpy.matmul>`.
Repeated subscript labels in one operand take the diagonal.
For example, ``np.einsum('ii', a)`` is equivalent to
:py:func:`np.trace(a) <numpy.trace>`.

In *implicit mode*, the chosen subscripts are important
since the axes of the output are reordered alphabetically.  This
means that ``np.einsum('ij', a)`` doesn't affect a 2D array, while
``np.einsum('ji', a)`` takes its transpose. Additionally,
``np.einsum('ij,jk', a, b)`` returns a matrix multiplication, while,
``np.einsum('ij,jh', a, b)`` returns the transpose of the
multiplication since subscript 'h' precedes subscript 'i'.

In *explicit mode* the output can be directly controlled by
specifying output subscript labels.  This requires the
identifier '->' as well as the list of output subscript labels.
This feature increases the flexibility of the function since
summing can be disabled or forced when required. The call
``np.einsum('i->', a)`` is like :py:func:`np.sum(a) <numpy.sum>`
if ``a`` is a 1-D array, and ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)``
is like :py:func:`np.diag(a) <numpy.diag>` if ``a`` is a square 2-D array.
The difference is that `einsum` does not allow broadcasting by default.
Additionally ``np.einsum('ij,jh->ih', a, b)`` directly specifies the
order of the output subscript labels and therefore returns matrix
multiplication, unlike the example above in implicit mode.

To enable and control broadcasting, use an ellipsis.  Default
NumPy-style broadcasting is done by adding an ellipsis
to the left of each term, like ``np.einsum('...ii->...i', a)``.
``np.einsum('...i->...', a)`` is like
:py:func:`np.sum(a, axis=-1) <numpy.sum>` for array ``a`` of any shape.
To take the trace along the first and last axes,
you can do ``np.einsum('i...i', a)``, or to do a matrix-matrix
product with the left-most indices instead of rightmost, one can do
``np.einsum('ij...,jk...->ik...', a, b)``.

When there is only one operand, no axes are summed, and no output
parameter is provided, a view into the operand is returned instead
of a new array.  Thus, taking the diagonal as ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)``
produces a view (changed in version 1.10.0).

`einsum` also provides an alternative way to provide the subscripts and
operands as ``einsum(op0, sublist0, op1, sublist1, ..., [sublistout])``.
If the output shape is not provided in this format `einsum` will be
calculated in implicit mode, otherwise it will be performed explicitly.
The examples below have corresponding `einsum` calls with the two
parameter methods.

Views returned from einsum are now writeable whenever the input array
is writeable. For example, ``np.einsum('ijk...->kji...', a)`` will now
have the same effect as :py:func:`np.swapaxes(a, 0, 2) <numpy.swapaxes>`
and ``np.einsum('ii->i', a)`` will return a writeable view of the diagonal
of a 2D array.

Added the ``optimize`` argument which will optimize the contraction order
of an einsum expression. For a contraction with three or more operands
this can greatly increase the computational efficiency at the cost of
a larger memory footprint during computation.

Typically a 'greedy' algorithm is applied which empirical tests have shown
returns the optimal path in the majority of cases. In some cases 'optimal'
will return the superlative path through a more expensive, exhaustive
search. For iterative calculations it may be advisable to calculate
the optimal path once and reuse that path by supplying it as an argument.
An example is given below.

See :py:func:`numpy.einsum_path` for more details.

Examples
--------
>>> a = np.arange(25).reshape(5,5)
>>> b = np.arange(5)
>>> c = np.arange(6).reshape(2,3)

Trace of a matrix:

>>> np.einsum('ii', a)
60
>>> np.einsum(a, [0,0])
60
>>> np.trace(a)
60

Extract the diagonal (requires explicit form):

>>> np.einsum('ii->i', a)
array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])
>>> np.einsum(a, [0,0], [0])
array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])
>>> np.diag(a)
array([ 0,  6, 12, 18, 24])

Sum over an axis (requires explicit form):

>>> np.einsum('ij->i', a)
array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])
>>> np.einsum(a, [0,1], [0])
array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])
>>> np.sum(a, axis=1)
array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])

For higher dimensional arrays summing a single axis can be done
with ellipsis:

>>> np.einsum('...j->...', a)
array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])
>>> np.einsum(a, [Ellipsis,1], [Ellipsis])
array([ 10,  35,  60,  85, 110])

Compute a matrix transpose, or reorder any number of axes:

>>> np.einsum('ji', c)
array([[0, 3],
       [1, 4],
       [2, 5]])
>>> np.einsum('ij->ji', c)
array([[0, 3],
       [1, 4],
       [2, 5]])
>>> np.einsum(c, [1,0])
array([[0, 3],
       [1, 4],
       [2, 5]])
>>> np.transpose(c)
array([[0, 3],
       [1, 4],
       [2, 5]])

Vector inner products:

>>> np.einsum('i,i', b, b)
30
>>> np.einsum(b, [0], b, [0])
30
>>> np.inner(b,b)
30

Matrix vector multiplication:

>>> np.einsum('ij,j', a, b)
array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])
>>> np.einsum(a, [0,1], b, [1])
array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])
>>> np.dot(a, b)
array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])
>>> np.einsum('...j,j', a, b)
array([ 30,  80, 130, 180, 230])

Broadcasting and scalar multiplication:

>>> np.einsum('..., ...', 3, c)
array([[ 0,  3,  6],
       [ 9, 12, 15]])
>>> np.einsum(',ij', 3, c)
array([[ 0,  3,  6],
       [ 9, 12, 15]])
>>> np.einsum(3, [Ellipsis], c, [Ellipsis])
array([[ 0,  3,  6],
       [ 9, 12, 15]])
>>> np.multiply(3, c)
array([[ 0,  3,  6],
       [ 9, 12, 15]])

Vector outer product:

>>> np.einsum('i,j', np.arange(2)+1, b)
array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
       [0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])
>>> np.einsum(np.arange(2)+1, [0], b, [1])
array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
       [0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])
>>> np.outer(np.arange(2)+1, b)
array([[0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
       [0, 2, 4, 6, 8]])

Tensor contraction:

>>> a = np.arange(60.).reshape(3,4,5)
>>> b = np.arange(24.).reshape(4,3,2)
>>> np.einsum('ijk,jil->kl', a, b)
array([[4400., 4730.],
       [4532., 4874.],
       [4664., 5018.],
       [4796., 5162.],
       [4928., 5306.]])
>>> np.einsum(a, [0,1,2], b, [1,0,3], [2,3])
array([[4400., 4730.],
       [4532., 4874.],
       [4664., 5018.],
       [4796., 5162.],
       [4928., 5306.]])
>>> np.tensordot(a,b, axes=([1,0],[0,1]))
array([[4400., 4730.],
       [4532., 4874.],
       [4664., 5018.],
       [4796., 5162.],
       [4928., 5306.]])

Writeable returned arrays (since version 1.10.0):

>>> a = np.zeros((3, 3))
>>> np.einsum('ii->i', a)[:] = 1
>>> a
array([[1., 0., 0.],
       [0., 1., 0.],
       [0., 0., 1.]])

Example of ellipsis use:

>>> a = np.arange(6).reshape((3,2))
>>> b = np.arange(12).reshape((4,3))
>>> np.einsum('ki,jk->ij', a, b)
array([[10, 28, 46, 64],
       [13, 40, 67, 94]])
>>> np.einsum('ki,...k->i...', a, b)
array([[10, 28, 46, 64],
       [13, 40, 67, 94]])
>>> np.einsum('k...,jk', a, b)
array([[10, 28, 46, 64],
       [13, 40, 67, 94]])

Chained array operations. For more complicated contractions, speed ups
might be achieved by repeatedly computing a 'greedy' path or pre-computing
the 'optimal' path and repeatedly applying it, using an `einsum_path`
insertion (since version 1.12.0). Performance improvements can be
particularly significant with larger arrays:

>>> a = np.ones(64).reshape(2,4,8)

Basic `einsum`: ~1520ms  (benchmarked on 3.1GHz Intel i5.)

>>> for iteration in range(500):
...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a)

Sub-optimal `einsum` (due to repeated path calculation time): ~330ms

>>> for iteration in range(500):
...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a,
...         optimize='optimal')

Greedy `einsum` (faster optimal path approximation): ~160ms

>>> for iteration in range(500):
...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a, optimize='greedy')

Optimal `einsum` (best usage pattern in some use cases): ~110ms

>>> path = np.einsum_path('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a,
...     optimize='optimal')[0]
>>> for iteration in range(500):
...     _ = np.einsum('ijk,ilm,njm,nlk,abc->',a,a,a,a,a, optimize=path)
